alvanizing and protecting work and pugnacious style earned him the epithet Dagger John. When the interests of his church and ethnic community were at stake, Hughes acted with purpose and clarity.In Dagger John, Loughery reveals Hughes’s life as it unfolded amid turbulent times for the religious and ethnic minority he represented. Hughes the public figure comes to the fore, illuminated by Loughery’s retelling of his interactions with, and responses to, every major figure of his era, including his critics (Walt Whitman, James Gordon Bennett, and Horace Greeley) and his admirers (Henry Clay, Stephen Douglas, and Abraham Lincoln). Loughery peels back the layers of the public life of this complicated man, showing how he reveled in the controversies he provoked and believed he had lived to see many of his goals achieved until his dreams came crashing down during the Draft Riots of 1863 when violence set Manhattan ablaze.To know "Dagger" John Hughes is to understand the United States during a painful period of growth as the nation headed toward civil war. Dagger John’s successes and failures, his public relationships and private trials, and his legacy in the Irish Catholic community and beyond provide context and layers of detail for the larger history of a modern culture unfolding in his wake.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBishopszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aIrish AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aNew York History. 4aReligious Studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Religious.2bisacsh  aIrish immigration, Catholicism, St. Patrick's Cathedral, slavery, New York Draft Riots.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR Single-User eBook-Package 2018z978311070864608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete 